Class DoublyLinkedList

java.lang.Object
DoublyLinkedList
class DoublyLinkedList
extends java.lang.Object
Next class Builds the double linked list and begins to work with the nodes built in the previous class Node

  • Constructor Details

    • DoublyLinkedList

      public DoublyLinkedList()
      skeleton of a double linked list includes a head and a tail

  • Method Details

    • isEmpty

      public boolean isEmpty()
      Checks if the first node is empty as I don't believe a linked list can have a null value first, if the first value is null then the array is empty
      Returns:
      If the first value (head) is null

    • insertFirst

      public void insertFirst​(int num)
      Inserts a number into the linked list in the FRONT of the list. Number inserted will push other nodes further down the chain
      Parameters:
      num - NUmber being inserted into the list

    • insertLast

      public void insertLast​(int num)
      Inserts a number at the end of the linked list.
      Parameters:
      num - Accepts the number being entered into the end of the list

    • insertAfter

      public boolean insertAfter​(int numToFind, int newNumber)
      Inserts a new number into the linked list AFTER a specific number. If a person wanted to enter the number 9 AFTER the number 20 in the linked list, this method would achieve that.
      Parameters:
      numToFind - The number being used as an identifier to which the next value is added.
      newNumber - The number being added into the list after the numToFind
      Returns:
      true If the number exists in the list, a true is returned. If not then false

    • deleteFirstNode

      public Node deleteFirstNode()
      Deletes the first node value inside of the list. this causes the next value in the list to become the first value
      Returns:
      The value of the node being deleted

    • deleteLastNode

      public Node deleteLastNode()
      Deletes the last node value inside of the linked list. as it is the last value, the previous value tail just needs to be set as null.
      Returns:
      Returns the number being deleted off the back of the list

    • searchAndDelete

      public Node searchAndDelete​(int number)
      searches for and deletes a specific number inside of the linked list.
      Parameters:
      number - the number which is being searched for by the user is entered into the method.
      Returns:
      returns the number that was removed from the list. Also returns the number if it was not present inside of the list.

    • printForwards

      public void printForwards()
      Prints out the contents of the node values inside of the list. First node to the last node.

    • printBackwards

      public void printBackwards()
      Prints out the node values inside of the list. however, this one prints the list in reverse order
